review_blob: The last but by no means least of my NZ Beery trilogy thanks to Greig and Ostreetbrewery! Oh what a beauty, this slides nicely into my top three double ipas and not one of them is from the US! This is my kind of beer though, big juicy green tasting hops like youve just picked em and stuffed them into a glass and yet the best thing about it is how light it feels on the palate, certainly doesnt feel like 8.5%...i chopped this down in about half an hour on a sunday afternoon...and then had a snooze! Loved it!

What a fantastically interesting beer, i have a problem with smoked beers in that ive never found one smokey enough, this beer almost gets there. Easily the most interesting beer ive drunk all year i found this to be ridiculously evocative, it took me on a journey of flash backs to BBQs and campfires of my past and remembrances of great times. I loved the way my senses recalibrated while drinking this beer, they went from shocked smokiness with my first sip to realising the subtle nuances in the underlying beer towards the end of the glass. Oh how i wished this was in a 750ml bottle, oh how i wished i could buy it over here!

Happy days, got sent this from NZ in a Muss bottle, was tempted to open this with a fish slice but refrained...my first pumpkin beer too so its all excitement at my house! Pours a lovely copper hue with a volumous off white head, before i start blabbing on about aromas and flavours and all that shite ive gotta say that on the face of it a 6.8%, 22ibu, spiced pumpkin beer didnt really rattle my tree...oh how wrong was I! Aroma, pleasantly spicy, cinnamon, nutmeg, clove? In the mouth its full and caramelly with a lovely, well integrated roasted pumpkin/spice combo. The good thing about the spices is that theyre not overdone, cinnamon can be a nightmare but these are perfect, they enhance but do not overpower. Heres me assuming cinnamon again but i could be wrong, im not the best at picking spices! My favourite thing about this beer is the aftertaste...have i just eaten a plate of roasted pumpkin? It certainly tastes like that! Briliant and delicious! My next two NZ beers have a lot to live up to!

I havent done any ratings for a while but i thought id come out of retirement for this one....What an amazing beer! Sat drinking this outside 57 Thomas st in the sun yesterday...the plan was to make the trek to Manchester for an American beer festival, after tasting Dobber though I didnt even bother, just kept drinking it and then went home...I knew Id only be disappointed if I drank something else!

Tried this at the marble arch yesterday...as soon as i was handed this pint i realised id made a mistake....Its all well and good waiting for the doors to open at 12 like a proper alcy but this was first off and pretty warm...ah well i thought as i wandered back to my table thisll be the tester...will it taste good after who knows how long in the lines? I gave it a sniff and thought holy crap I gave it a taste and thought by jingos this is fantastic! yes ridiculously warm but easily still one of the best pints ive had all year! Drank it in about 15 minutes then switched to dobber...aarrgghh another warm one! am i the only person in this bar drinking the strong stuff at midday...apparently so...ahh well good times! I suppose i should be harsh in the rating given that it was warm but i say bollocks to that! After the dobber i popped round to 57 Thomas and had one on stillage...alright tasted two different ways in one day...tell you what my afternoon went fast after those three pints!

Tried thanks to Stu and Kel at the coach in a kind of impromptu tasting. Must have been one of the last ones in existence! Read a couple of other peoples ratings...yep i do remember us saying that it looked fantastic...fantastic beer really, yep loads of pineapple, citrus etc...i reckon this is up there with alesmith IPA and kicks ass all over meantime ipa. Not sure why we made the comparison with meantime but It struck me at the time as an ipa that seemed more traditional like what an ipa should be like...which is what meantime sort of claim...
Anyway overall a really great beer, love to drink more of it, it messed me up so much i tried to sleep in a dogs bed...

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: I get a bit fed up with beer and food matching what i tend to enjoy and remember more is beer and situation or movie matches....i drunk this while watching a re-run of the Goonies on TV and what a fantastic pairing! The beer had a creamy and herbal palate that seemed to match the overtones of pirate buried treasure well. On the nose it was all cloves and nutmeg that i think went fantastically well with the 80s wardrobe that the heroes and heroines were wearing. it didnt look very good in the glass but thats ok because neither does the cast! To top off a fantastic matched with a fantastic movie!

Tinned peaches on the nose, blunt bitter palate without hop flavours, more tinned peaches on the palate....was hoping for more from this because in the bottle i think this was my first introduction to the world of hops!
Slightly toffee nose, sweet nothing much to it really slight dishwash character

I like Oakham they put a shed load of hops in everything even a wheatbeer! This is a really interesting twist on a wheat beer and is spectacularly refreshing! ive marked it down on appearance only because its crystal clear

cask at the coach and horses. What initially strikes me is the amazing malt nose on this, roast coffee, chocolate...amazing! If im not after hops this is the beer id drink regularly, emminently drinkable and massively flavourful.

1985 vintage. Tough one to rate, im a bit torn as to wether i liked this or not....on balance i did. Smelt really good, winey, sherry. Fairly thin mouthfeel which i expected and flavours varied from worcester sauce, sherry, intense molasses and then a touch of sourness. Finishes really quite bitter.

Hot damn this is one of the best fruit lambics that ive had.....i love that you smell it and it smells like sweet cherries....no warning for the palate assault thats to come! Dry? holy shit this is so mouth puckeringly dry that my lips were stuck to my teeth! Love it!
Tried thanks to Kelly. mens toilet block on the nose, egg and iron flavours to follow....hey all flavours are possible with wild yeast and i kinda liked this...
On tap at the Rake. Looks good, tightly packed tan head, deep black colour. starts off winey, sweet with a kick ass bitter finish. Not a bad Impy stout but not the best ive had.

Tried at the Rake, Pours a pale straw, touch of dirt in the flavour...lines perhaps? Nicely bitter but not a hell of a lot of flavour with it, a touch one dimensional....not sure if i should do a rating on this but i guess i should take it as it comes

Tried on handpump at the coach and horses thanks to Cat! Amazing aroma on this beer, really sharp zesty lemongrass citrus that i loved. fantastic refreshing beer with an amazing use of hops citrus and passionfruit abound....almost prefered this to Jaipur...but not quite!
Hmmm whats the kindest thing i can say about this...its wet i guess. insipid rubbish, cant believe that people ask for a carling top to make it more drinkable....its stupidly sweet anyway!
Hmmmm what a mistaker to maker....thought this would be nice sitting in the sun....it made me feel like i was a teenage girl drinking an alcopop

How this has rated so poorly i dont know this is a fantastic beer! Big toffee aromas followed by toffee on the palate with a touch of marmite that is cleaned out nicely by a late bitterness. This really ticks all the boxes for me, great body, balanced malt and it looks great
Tried at the Bree Louise. Pours a deep chocolate with ruby highlights, dark choc fudge on the nose, full palate demerara sugar, toffee with a huge coffee hit in the finish

Tried at the Bree louise on stillage, not much condition to this but it still tastes fantastic! a blend of rosemary and sauv blanc on the nose, floral flavours, elderflower and a nice grape skin bitterness

I was immediately struck by then sheer beauty of this as i poured it, the head was a lovely coffee cremer colour with tightly packed bubbles. Coffee, milk chocolate ans a touch of smoke on the nose....could do with more smoke! palate is smooth with a touch of smoke again...theres obviously no fire because theres not much smoke! A good beer overall but a bit misleading on the label.
Popular beer with Harveys fans....there was almost a riot on Friday when it wasnt ready to go on! Average beer for me really...hoppier finish than the dark mild, perhaps a touch of green apple...
Pours a dark Ruby, Raisins and orange peel nose, fruity with a good bitter finish, nice beer
Tried at the wheatsheaf borough fairly hohum bitter that never really lifts itself above a distictly average rating....very nondeScript!

On cask at the princess head in Richmond. This always surprises me how light the colour is in the glass but i find that incredibly becoming. Great beer, bags of the orangey character you usually get but my only complaint about this was a touch of hot alcohol on the palate, never mind it went down well with my bangers and mash!
Tried at the Charles Dickens amazing mild! not quite as roasty as the bottle but smoother and probably better balanced for it really glad i popped in for a swifty now!

I was looking forward to this but i was actually underwhelmed when i tried it, i think "meh" sums it up, sulpharon the nose, fruity palate little to no hop presence...apparently supposed to convert lager drinkers but i doubt that! I reckon a beer like Sierra nevada pale would be more likely to convert lager drinkers because it has that refreshing component that they look for in the cold and fizzyness...

Waste of time assessing aroma at the moment damn cold! Well this is my first time with spitfire on cask and im quite pleased! Looks good inn the glass and my main impression was a good malty body and a delicious green/wet hop flavour with a decent bitterness....not to shabby really!

Holy CRAP! what a beer!!! dammit i wish i could smell things at the moment cursed blocked nose! This is a fantastic beer crazy flavours for the alc % lovely sweet body then kazaam a hop tirade thats almost as bitter as twisted hop IPA! amazing beer, without doubt the best tasting beer ive had since ive been in the UK! damn i need more of this now!

I bought this hoping for a rauchbier not an element of the character....ah well it was still a good beer but i cant help being disappointed a little bit....overall impression..smooth with a capital smoo!
Pours a russet with ruby highlights, great carbonation. Smooth sweet chocolate, not to much of the nutty goodness its more about the choc...more like a sweet old ale than anything

I had this when it was released at the Eastbourne beer festival a few years back and thought it was fantastic...wish i could remember it a bit better! This is the bottled version 6.5% not so good....cooked on the nose and very muddied flavours, sweet boiled vege malt, not much hop presence...tastes like its had the shit boiled out of it!
On cask for the wetherspoon beer festival and just so happens to be page 394 of MJs good beer guide...bready yeast, touch acidic, bitter finish...it was ok but i wont be having it again
Pretty uninspiring cider on draught, sweet, fizzy, the cider version of lolly water.
beer_name: Westons Stowford Press Medium Dry Cider

review_blob: Not sure whats going on with the picture on the left....looks like a sherry! Viscous thick body, tastes of sherry and a touch of cognac, great beer!

Tried at the wheatsheaf under the hop exchange. Looks a touch unsettled more of a chill haze than anything but i dont mind that at all. Oozes with fresh citrus hop flavours and a firm malt presence lovely afternoon pint.

Tried at the Hamilton Hall. Not as much aroma as the usual epic....i wonder if a sparkler would be a good idea....looks slightly darker although i could be wrong. Fantastic body to this, it really is made by the great palate! Although there is probably less hop flavour and bitterness the hops seem more apparent like its had a hop bag dunked into the glass, not over the top but nicely there, it made the sides of my tongue prickle. Loved it, better oh so much better than the original!

This beer reminds me of sitting on Greigs front lawn after buying a load of beer from Hamilton Wine Company, pity the beer isnt as good as i remember...just doesnt seem as nutty as i remembered...palate was a touch this...i was pretty underwhelmed by this.

Bottle from utobeer. Pours a dark chocolate with tan head rich dark fruit flavours are followed by a malty slightly smokey nose. Fruityness is then cleaned away by a surprising bitter finish great stuff!
UPDATED: APR 19, 2009

Dried strawberries and vanilla essenceon the nose. Murky rose pink/red colour tastes like sickly cough mixture...didnt finish it! FROTHINGSLOSH i like fruit beers but unfortunately this is commercial pap!
Tried at the market porter. Rose petal and dried cut grass on the nose, good body, great floral citrus flavours fantastic beer i could do with another 5-6 to be fair....
Close to zero hop aroma, no malt body and a pile of bitterness doesnt make for a good beer....this wasnt....drain pour!

Absolutely fantastic pint at the mabel tavern, ive been waiting a while to try this on cask, love the bottled version but this was fantastic. everything i like in the bottle but dialed up a notch with a great body! huge fruity body...stalky raisins perhaps and a great lingering bitterness....we walked down to russel square and i could still taste it 20 mins later!

On stillage at the Charles Dickens. Pours absolute black without much head...hey its on stillage i forgive it for that! Intense smoke roasty nose thats mimicked in the flavours, the best thing about this is the awesome oily palate love it!

Had at the Charles Dickens. Wow this couldnt be more opposite to the commercial deScription! I wrote in my little book that this bitter had fully embraced and gone down the rich malt pathway not much in the way of hop presence and is a little blah because of it.

I bought this hoping for more hops but was sadly disappointed in fact i couldnt be more wrong, that being said its still not a bad beer, actually pretty well balanced and has a zesty fruit kind of finish to it, tasty beer!
UPDATED: APR 12, 2009
